},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105611","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105611"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman is admitted to hospital with a three-day history of severe gastroenteritis with profuse diarrhoea. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears dehydrated. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 105/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Blood tests reveal a serum potassium of 2.8 mmol/L (3.5-5.0). The nurse-in-charge shows you her ECG.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely set of ECG changes?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Deep Q waves and ST elevation","Peaked T waves and shortened QT interval","Shortened PR interval with delta waves","Right bundle branch block pattern","Tall U waves with flattened T waves"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with severe hypokalaemia secondary to gastrointestinal losses. The characteristic ECG changes of hypokalaemia become evident when serum potassium falls below 3.0 mmol/L.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETall U waves with flattened T waves\u003C/strong\u003E are the classic ECG findings in hypokalaemia. The U wave appears as a positive deflection after the T wave, most prominently seen in leads V2 and V3. The T wave becomes progressively flatter as potassium levels fall. Other changes can include ST-segment depression and increased P wave amplitude.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeaked T waves and shortened QT interval\u003C/strong\u003E are characteristic of hyperkalaemia, not hypokalaemia. These changes typically appear when potassium levels rise above 5.5 mmol/L.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDeep Q waves and ST elevation\u003C/strong\u003E are usually seen in myocardial infarction and are not associated with electrolyte disturbances.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERight bundle branch block pattern\u003C/strong\u003E represents a conduction abnormality and is not associated with hypokalaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EShortened PR interval with delta waves\u003C/strong\u003E is characteristic of Wolff-Parkinson-White syndrome, a pre-excitation syndrome, and is not related to potassium abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe ECG changes in hypokalaemia are clinically significant as they may predispose to cardiac arrhythmias, particularly in the setting of digoxin therapy or acute coronary syndrome. The mechanism involves altered cardiac cell membrane potential and delayed ventricular repolarisation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hypokalaemia causes characteristic ECG changes including U waves, ST depression, and flattened T waves.","Significant gastrointestinal losses are a common cause of hypokalaemia.","ECG changes in hypokalaemia typically occur when serum potassium is less than 3.0 mmol/L."],"references":["Levis J. ECG Diagnosis: Hypokalemia. The Permanente Journal. 2012 Apr 1;16(2). Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3383164/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88040"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19039"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88040","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88040"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-10T22:38:57+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-10T22:38:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11773"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105611"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":